{
  "texts": [
    "A Humberstone frame is a tuple F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩, where ⟨S, ⊑⟩ is a poset, R i is a binary relation on S, and P = RO(S, ⊑), such that F satisfies up-R, R-down, and:• R-refinability ++ -if xR i y, then ∃x ′ ⊑ x ∀x ′′ ⊑ x ′, x ′′ R i y.A Humberstone model is a tuple M = ⟨F, π⟩ where F is a Humberstone frame and π: Φ → P. (In fact, Humberstone [1981] took π to be a partial function, but that approach is equivalent to the approach of this paper, as explained in Remark 8.3.",
    "Later Humberstone [2011, p. 900] took the total function approach.",
    ")Since up-R and R-refinability ++ together imply the conditions of Proposition 2.30, the set P of admissible propositions in a Humberstone frame is closed under ■ i, and as previously noted, RO(S, ⊑) is automatically closed under ∩ and ⊃.",
    "Thus, Humberstone frames are partial-state frames as in Definition 2.1, and since they satisfy P = RO(S, ⊑), they are full possibility frames as in Definition 2.21.Humberstone's R-refinability ++ condition is not implied by any combination of the other conditions discussed in this section.",
    "In contrast to Fact 2.38, the powerset possibilization of a Kripke frame is not necessarily a Humberstone frame (see Appendix § B.1)."
  ]
}